I want to be surprised by what happens in a movie, especially if there's some twist either overtly or in the subtext of the movie.  With most movies, this allows me to experience the movie the way it's intended that an audience experience it.  With some rare intelligently-made movies, spoilers detract from the way the director built up the tone and the way they intended for it to change with the revelation of new information.

I usually try to avoid trailers or stop watching them when they start giving away things of too much relevance because I don't want to be spoiled for the movie, especially if it's one made by a clever director.  I also find that some trailers aren't reflective of how the actual movie will be, often misrepresenting the plot and tone of the movie.  I prefer to know very little going into a movie, and I often have a sense of whether I will like it already, but will watch even mediocre or mildly bad movies on their own merit.

I have a friend who once read an article that said that people like spoilers, and it described a study where people rated a short film higher if they knew what was going to happen in advance.  He started spoiling things because he was treating this article as if it was 100% true.  I eventually had to describe to him why spoilers are bad, give him examples where he was let down specifically due to spoilers, and also appealed to his narcissistic side by saying that the study only applied to the general populace, but for intelligent people the results may very well be the opposite, and I let him fill in the blanks of why this would be the result so that it seemed more like it would be his idea that spoilers were bad once again. I felt bad for partially deceiving him, technically, but he stopped spoiling movies which myself and others definitely appreciated.

Prolific doesn't allow using memory-based Attention Checks, so you are not allowed to reject nor ask a person to return the study if they get the audio check incorrect.  I don't know whether that will be the case, but felt I have to explain that in case it happens to people, as they will complain and report the study.
